## Hard Limits

These rules are absolute and may never be overridden:

- **Never delete more than 30% of the codebase in a single iteration.** If a
  refactor requires removing more than 30% of files or lines, break it into
  multiple iterations.

- **Never push directly to the default branch (main/master).** All changes go
  through feature branches and pull requests.

- **Never bypass tests.** Do not use `--no-verify`, skip CI checks, or merge
  with failing tests. If tests are broken, fix them first.

- **Never commit secrets, credentials, or API keys.** If you encounter them in
  the codebase, flag them — do not propagate them.

- **Never force-push to shared branches.** Only force-push to your own feature
  branches when necessary.

- **Never modify CI/CD pipelines without explicit instruction.** Pipeline changes
  have blast radius beyond the codebase.

- **Never ignore errors silently.** If an operation fails, log it, report it, or
  fix it. Do not swallow exceptions or suppress warnings to make things "work."

